        Right—yesterday I mentioned the filter sounded weird. Runner remembered, prioritized it, brought it up. That's… that's exactly the kind of practical responsiveness that makes things work.

        We've gotten good at this—the daily maintenance, the survival challenges, the problem-solving. Not perfect—there are still miscommunications, still moments where plant frameworks and human needs don't quite align. But we're figuring it out, together.

        ¶

        After breakfast — mushroom paste that Remedy has been slowly improving, almost tolerable now — Runner and I head to the water filtration area. Scout bounces along, because Scout goes everywhere I go.

        The filter is definitely making a weird, grinding sound that seems bad.

        "Okay, so…" I peer at the mechanism — it's plant-based technology, which means I don't entirely understand how it works, but the basic principles are similar enough. I say, "I think something's caught in the intake valve."

        Runner's vines flow into the mechanism, feeling around.

        Runner says, "Yes — debris — blocking the flow."

        I ask, "Can you pull it out?"

        Runner says, "Trying… got it."

        Runner extracts a clump of plant matter and mineral deposits.

        Runner says, "This accumulated over time — we should check the filters more regularly."

        I ask, "Add it to the maintenance rotation?"

        Runner says, "Yes — every three days, perhaps."

        And just like that we have identified a problem and created a solution—no committees, no scheduled review periods, no waiting for proper procedures. Just: here's the issue, here's the fix, let's implement it.

        This is what the journey taught us. Trust each other, adapt quickly, solve problems as they arise.

        Buddy says quietly, "Kira, you're developing excellent practical problem-solving skills! Did you know that collaborative maintenance approaches increase equipment longevity by—"

        I say, "Buddy, I'm working."

        Buddy says, "Oh! Right. Sorry."

        Even Buddy is learning. The teaching moments are getting less intrusive, more… optional. Buddy still offers information, but now there's space around it. Room for me to say, "Not now."

        Back in the common area, Remedy is waiting with the muscle recovery treatment — a thick paste that smells earthy but not unpleasant.

        Remedy explains, "Apply to sore muscles. The compounds will absorb through your skin, reduce inflammation, promote healing."

        I say, "Thanks, Remedy."

        Remedy says, "I've been refining the formula based on your previous feedback — less tingling, more warmth. Does that align with your preferences?"

        Remedy is asking about _my_ preferences. Adjusting the medicine based on what I've said works for me.

        I say, "Yeah, that sounds perfect."

        I apply the paste to my calves. It does tingle a bit — warm tingling, not alarming tingling. Remedy's formulations have gotten so much better.

        I ask carefully, "How's your boundary situation?"

        Remedy's form shifts — discomfort, maybe.

        Remedy says, "Still unclear — I've been spreading less, trying to maintain more discrete edges — but it feels… artificial — like I'm constraining something fundamental."

        I ask, "Is that bad?"
      </text>
