        Remedy says, "I don't know — that's the problem. I don't know what's me making a choice versus me fighting my own nature."
        Remedy pauses.
        Remedy says, "But I appreciate you asking."

        It doesn't solve Remedy's existential crisis — I don't think that's solvable — but it does acknowledge it, make space for the uncertainty.

        The afternoon is maintenance tasks and small improvements. Scout and I reinforce a weak section of wall. Velvet reports that one of the environmental control systems needs adjustment. Florence stops by — wheeled in by one of the mobile platforms, carrying Elder Twist's pot — to discuss resource allocation for next month.

        It's all very… domestic — routine — the kind of daily work that makes a place livable.

        And we're good at it now.

        That realization hits me as I'm helping Runner organize the supply storage — we're actually good at this. The plants understand my needs better; I understand their frameworks — we've built a functional rhythm.

        I say — slowly — to Runner, "Have you noticed things are working better?"

        Runner says, "Yes — cooperation is smoother. Communication clearer. We're learning your patterns, you're learning ours."

        I say, "The journey helped, I think — nine days of figuring out how to work together."

        Runner says, "It did."
        Runner's vines wrap gently around a storage container, organizing it precisely. "But also the time since — every day we learn something new. Small adjustments that compound."

        Small adjustments that compound — yeah, that's exactly what it feels like.

        ¶

        That evening, gathered in the common area, Holloway says, "Elder Heartwood's response should arrive soon — another week, perhaps two."

        There's a collective sense of anticipation. The plants are hopeful — excited, even.

        Holloway says, "Elder Heartwood will provide the framework we need — the systematic understanding of human care that we've been missing."

        Florence adds, "It will explain the patterns — connect the individual solutions we've found into a coherent whole."

        Scout bounces — agreement, excitement.

        I want to share their enthusiasm — I do — but sitting here, looking around at the plants who've been helping me, thinking about everything we've figured out together…

        «Do we actually need Elder Heartwood to tell us how to do what we're already doing?»

        The thought feels almost disloyal. The plants have so much faith in Elder Heartwood's wisdom. They journeyed three territories to present the question, they've been waiting weeks for the response, they're counting on this.

        And maybe Elder Heartwood *WILL* have useful insights — ancient wisdom, vast perspective, understanding that connects everything.
      </text>
