        But also... we've been learning the real answers every day — through trial and error, and by paying attention to each other. Remedy refined the muscle-recovery paste based on my feedback, Runner is growing an understanding of boundaries, Holloway asks what I need instead of just scheduling what the manual recommends, Velvet's observations are deepening, and Scout's companionship is steady.

        Those are real — they're working.

        Holloway continues — "When the response comes, we'll finally understand how to properly care for you, Kira. The uncertainty will resolve."

        Everyone seems so sure, so hopeful.

        I don't want to undermine that — they've worked hard, they care deeply, they've been waiting for this answer. But I'm also starting to realize we might not need it the way they think we do.

        I say — "I'm sure it will be helpful."

        Which is probably true — even if it's not *THE* answer they're hoping for, Elder Heartwood's perspective might offer something useful — maybe.

        Scout curls up next to me, content. Velvet says the evening light is particularly good today. Runner asks if tomorrow we can check the ventilation system — there's a section that might need repair.

        This is my life now — daily maintenance with plant companions who are learning to care for me while I learn to work with them.

        We're not waiting for the real answer to arrive — we're already living it.

        But tomorrow, or next week, or whenever Elder Heartwood's response comes, I'll find out if the plants can see that too.
      </text>
